Causal Effect of Job Class on Wage of Males from the Atlantic Region of the United States

Fei Zhang, Kai Zhang, Hongyao Zhu

Jul 14, 2020

Background story

# Load the data
data("Wage")

# Clean the data
dat = Wage[, c(1:5,8,9,11)]
dat$A = Wage$jobclass

dat$race = as.factor(dat$race)
dat$education = as.factor(dat$education)
dat$health = as.factor(dat$health)
dat$health_ins = as.factor(dat$health_ins)
dat$A = as.factor(dat$A)

This dataset is used in the book “An Introduction to Statistical Learning” and was manually assembled by Steve Miller, of Open BI (www.openbi.com), from the March 2011 Supplement to Current Population Survey data. The original total dataset can be found at https://data.census.gov/mdat/#/ in the CPS Annual Social and Economic (March) Supplement. We downloaded the dataset Wage from package ISLR.

This dataset contains information about a group of 3000 males from the Atlantic region of the United States. Details of the code book of the dataset is shown in the appendix.

We are interested in the causal effect of job class to the wage in such a population.

Step 0: Scientific question

We are interesting in evaluating the effect of job class on the wage of males from the Atlantic region of the United States.

Covariates of interest will include:
\(W_1\): Age
\(W_2\): Race, including White, Black, Asian and Others
\(W_3\): Education level
\(W_4\): Martial status
\(W_5\): Health level of worker
\(W_6\): Year that wage information was recorded
\(W_7\): Whether worker has health insurance
\(A\): Exposure, type of job, including industrial and information job
\(Y\): Outcome, workers raw wage

Covariate \(W = \{W_1, W_2, W_3, W_4, W_5,W_6, W_7\}\)

Step 1: Causal model representing real knowledge

Our problem can be translated into the following structural causal model (SCM):

Endogenous nodes: \(X = (W, A, Y)\)
Background (exogenous) variables: \(U = (U_W,U_A,U_Y)\) ~ \(P^*\)
Structural equations F:

\[ \begin{align} W &\leftarrow f_{W}(U_{W}) \\ A &\leftarrow f_{A}(W, U_{A}) \\ Y &\leftarrow f_{Y}(W, A, U_{Y}) \\ \end{align} \]

The DAG of this SCM is shown below:

Fig1. The DAG of the SCM

Step 2: Counterfactuals & causal parameter

The counterfactuals are \(Y_1\) and \(Y_0\).

\(Y_0\): the solution of the equation \(f_Y\) under an intervention on the system of equations to set \(A=0\), e.g., all the observations had Industrial job class with input \(U=u\). \(Y_0=f_Y(W, A=0, U_Y)\)

\(Y_1\): the solution of the equation \(f_Y\) under an intervention on the system of equations to set \(A=1\), e.g., all the observations had Information job class with input \(U=u\). \(Y_1=f_Y(W, A=1, U_Y)\)

We first draw all the \(U\) from \(P^*\) and generate all \(W\) as deterministric function of all the \(U_W\). Then we set A deterministically to 1 in order to generate \(Y_1(U)\) as a deterministric function of \((W, A, U_Y)\). We can set A to 0 in order to generate \(Y_0(U)\) similarly.

The target causal parameter is the average treatment effect (ATE):

\[\begin{align*} \theta^*(\mathrm{P}^*) &= \mathrm{E}^*(Y_1) - \mathrm{E}^*(Y_0) \\ &= \mathrm{E}^*\big[ f_{Y}(W, 1, U_{Y}) \big] - \mathrm{E}^*\big[ f_{Y}(W, 0, U_{Y}) \big] \end{align*}\]

Our target causal parameter, ATE, is the difference in the expected counterfactual wage if all observations had an Information job class and the expected counterfactual wage if all observations had Industrial job class.

Step 3: Observed data & link to causal model

We assume that the observed data were generated by a system compatible with (described by) our structural causal model. The distribution of the background variables \(\mathrm{P}^*\) and the structural equations \(F\) identifies the distribution of the observed data \(O\). If we knew the distribution of \(U\) and the functions \(F\), we would know the distribution of \(O\). Thus, the causal model has implications for the distribution of \(O\). These implications are testable.

Step 4: Identification

In the original structural causal model, the target causal parameter is not identified from the observed data distribution. For identifiability to hold, we would need the following independence assumptions to hold: \(U_A \perp U_Y\) and (i) \(U_A \perp U_{W}\), or (ii) \(U_Y \perp U_{W}\). We also need the positivity assumption to hold \[ 0 < P(A=1|W=w) < 1 \] for all \(w\) for which \(\mathrm{P}(W=w) >0\). In terms of our dataset, there must be a positive probability of the subjects with Information job class within strata of baseline covariates.

In this study, we have covariates (age, marital status, race, education level, health status, health insurance, and the recording year), representing the objective conditions of a person. Subjective conditions like personality or personal preference may affect job classes but not the wage. Therefore, from a material perspective, give assumptions discussed above, our target causal parameter can be identified. And \(U_A \perp U_Y\), together with \(U_Y \perp U_W\) may be more plausible. More variables such as family members’ job class, family members’ wages may also be included.

Step 5: Specify the statistical estimand

The target statistical estimand is given by the G-Computation formula: \[\begin{align*} \theta &= \mathrm{E}\big[ \mathrm{E}(Y|A=1, W) - \mathrm{E}(Y|A=0,W) \big] \\ &= \sum_w \big[ \mathrm{E}(Y|A=1, W=w) -\mathrm{E}(Y|A=0, W=w) \big]\mathrm{P}(W=w) \end{align*}\]

Step 6: Estimate

The target causal parameter, the average treatment effect, was estimated using four different estimators, including G-Computation, IPTW, AIPW, and TMLE, using data-adaptive methods. When we apply an estimator to our observed data (\(n\) i.i.d. copies of \(O\) drawn from \(\mathrm{P}\)), we can get an estimate (a number). The estimator is a function of random variables, so it is a random variable. It has a distribution, which we can study theoretically or using simulations. An estimator is consistent if the point estimates converge (in probability) to the estimand as sample size \(n \rightarrow \infty\).

To estimate outcome variable ( Wage ), Super Learner includes libraries in the following:

  • biglasso.

  • glmnet.

  • Gradient Boosting Machine (n.tree = 100, max.depth = 1, learing rate = 0.1).

  • Random Forest (n.tree = 500).

  • XGBoost (n.tree = 500, max.depth = 3, learning rate = 0.01).

To estimate exposure variable ( type of job ), Super Learner includes libraries in the following:

  • Logistic Regression.

  • K Nearest Neighbors (K = 50).

  • Gradient Boost Machine (n.tree = 1000, max.depth = 1, learning rate = 0.1)

  • Random Forest (n.trees = 100)

  • XGBoost (n.tree = 1000, max.depth = 1, learning rate = 0.1).

The process of tuning hyperparameters of the above algorithms is shown in Appendix, with newly defined superlearner libraries. By tuning the hyperparameters, especially for ensemble methods, we achieved higher accuracy and less computing time.

# tuned libraries for estimating outcome
gbm.outcome = function(...) {
  SL.gbm(...,gbm.trees = 100, interaction.depth = 1, shrinkage = 0.1)
}

rf.outcome = function(...){
  SL.ranger(...,num.trees = 500)
}

xg.outcome = function(...){
  SL.xgboost(...,ntrees = 500, max_depth = 3, shrinkage = 0.01)
}

outcome_library = c("SL.biglasso", "SL.glmnet", "SL.mean",
                    "rf.outcome", "gbm.outcome", "xg.outcome")

# tuned libraries for estimating exposure
gbm.exposure = function(...) {
  SL.gbm(...,gbm.trees = 1000, interaction.depth = 1, shrinkage = 0.1)
}

rf.exposure = function(...){
  SL.ranger(...,num.trees = 100)
}

xg.exposure = function(...){
  SL.xgboost(...,ntrees = 1000, max_depth = 1, shrinkage = 0.1)
}

knn.exposure = function(...){
  SL.knn(...,k = 50)
}

exposure_library = c("gbm.exposure", "rf.exposure",
                     "xg.exposure", "knn.exposure",
                     "SL.glm", "SL.mean")

To calculate the standard error of these four estimators, the bootstrap method was used. We created a function four_est() to simultaneously perform bootstrap on the four estimators and adopt parallel computing (snow) to accelerate computing. Specifically, we resampled the data with replacement 200 times (See Appendix).

library(boot)
# configure snow for parallel computing
clusterExport(cluster, outcome_library)
clusterExport(cluster, exposure_library)
clusterExport(cluster, "four_est")
results = boot(data=dat, 
               statistic = four_est, 
               R = 200,
               SL.m = outcome_library, 
               SL.g = exposure_library,
               parallel = "snow", 
               cl = cluster)

# save the boostrap results
save(results,"boot_data.RData")

Outcome

For Super Learner estimating outcome variables, the mean risk of a simple mean algorithm is estimated at 1742.15, which the highest among all methods. And this value is the benchmark for all algorithms in this study. Based on the result, we can find that all the methods we used are better than the simple mean algorithm. The random forest performs best among them, and its mean risk is estimated at 1144.64. In conclusion, for the outcome, a random forest algorithm performs best. And for the outcome, general linear regression performs best.

Simple substitution estimator based on the G-Computation

The G-Computation estimator is:

\[ \hat{\theta}_{G-comp} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \bigg( \hat{\mathrm{E}}(Y_i | A_i=1,W_i) - \hat{\mathrm{E}}(Y_i | A_i=0,W_i) \bigg) \]

where \(\hat{\mathrm{E}}(Y| A,W)\) is the estimator of the conditional mean outcome given the exposure (children attending the after school reading program or not) and baseline covariates \(\mathrm{E}(Y|A,W)\). Consistency of the simple (non-targeted) substitution estimator depends on the consistent estimation of the conditional mean outcome \(\mathrm{E}(Y|A,W)\).

SuperLearner Result

SL.outcome=snowSuperLearner(dat$wage, X, family = gaussian(),
                            cvControl = list(V=10),
                            SL.library = outcome_library,
                            cluster = cluster)

ma = predict(SL.outcome, newdata = X, onlySL = TRUE)$pred
m1 = predict(SL.outcome, newdata = X1, onlySL = TRUE)$pred
m0 = predict(SL.outcome, newdata = X0, onlySL = TRUE)$pred

mean(m1-m0); # 3.254

Bootstrap Result

The bootstrap result for G-Computation is shown in the following figure. The estimates look as though they are following a normal distribution, though the substitution estimator is not asymptotically normal in theory.

Standard (unstabilized) inverse probability weighted estimator (IPTW)

The IPTW estimator is:

\[ \hat{\theta}_{IPTW} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n \left( \frac{\mathrm{I}(A_i=1)}{\hat{\mathrm{P}}(A_i=1|W_i)} - \frac{\mathrm{I}(A_i=0)}{\hat{\mathrm{P}}(A_i=0|W_i)} \right) Y_i \]

where \(\hat{\mathrm{P}}(A=1|W)\) is the estimator of the exposure mechanism (i.e. the conditional probability of attending the program, given the baseline covariates). Consistency of IPTW estimators depends on consistent estimation of the exposure mechanism \(\mathrm{P}(A|W)\).

Next, we used IPTW without stabilization and truncation to estimate the causal parameter, which is 4.726.

H_AW = c(1:nrow(dat))
H_AW[dat$A==1] = 1/gw[dat$A==1]
H_AW[dat$A==0] = -1/(1-gw[dat$A==0])
H_1W = 1/gw
H_0W = -1/(1-gw)
mean(H_AW*dat$wage)
## [1] 4.725991

Next, as the guidelines require, we truncating \(\hat{P}(A=1|W)\) by 1% and 5% to evaluating the sensitivity to different truncation level (though the minimal value for \(\hat{P}(A=1|W)\) is 0.163, which we think there is no need to truncate). We dropped the smallest 1% (30 observations) of g(W) and 5% (150 observations) of g(W) from the dataset and calculated ATE using IPTW with truncated g(W).

The estimated ATE using IPTW is 5.588, with 1% level of truncation.

gw.1 = gw[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]
gw.5 = gw[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]
H_AW.1 = H_AW[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]
H_AW.5 = H_AW[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]
H_1W.1 = 1/gw.1
H_1W.5 = 1/gw.5
H_0W.1 = -1/(1-gw.1)
H_0W.5 = -1/(1-gw.5)
mean(H_AW.1*dat$wage[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)])
## [1] 5.588054

The estimated ATE using IPTW is 9.133 with 5% level of truncation.

mean(H_AW.5*dat$wage[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)])
## [1] 9.133023

Bootstrap Result

The bootstrap result for IPTW estimators is shown below. All three seem like following a normal distribution, though this is not guaranteed by theory (asymptotical linearity and normality is not the property of IPTW).

Augmented inverse probability weighted estimator (AIPW)

The AIPW estimator is:

\[ \hat{\theta}_{AIPW} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \bigg\{\frac{A_i}{\hat{g}(W_i)} [Y_i-\hat{m}(W_i)] + \hat{m}(W_i) \bigg\} \]

Where \(\hat{g}(W_i)\) is our estimated \(P(A=1|W)\), and \(\hat{m}(W)\) is our estimated \(E(Y|A=1, W)\). Implementation requires estimation of both the conditional mean function \(\mathrm{E}(Y|A,W)\) and the exposure mechanism \(g(W)=\mathrm{P}(A=1|W)\). Double robust estimators are consistent if either \(\mathrm{E}(Y|A,W)\) or \(\mathrm{P}(A|W)\) are estimated consistently. If both \(\mathrm{E}(Y|A,W)\) and \(\mathrm{P}(A|W)\) are estimated consistently, AIPW will be efficient (achieve the lowest possible asymptotic variance). These asymptotic properties describe what happens when sample size goes to infinity and also translate into lower bias and variance in finite samples.

SuperLearner Result

We first implement AIPW without truncating \(\hat{P}(A=1|W)\), which is 7.417.

mean(H_1W*(dat$wage-m1)+m1 - (H_0W*(dat$wage-m0)+m0))
## [1] 7.416641

Similarly, 1% and 5% truncation levels were applied to AIPW estimator. The AIPW estimated ATE with truncation level of 1% is 7.481.

m1.1 = m1[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]
m1.5 = m1[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]
m0.1 = m0[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]
m0.5 = m0[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]
mean(H_1W.1*(dat$wage[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]-m1.1)+m1.1 - (H_0W.1*(dat$wage[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]-m0.1)+m0.1))
## [1] 7.481174

The AIPW estimated ATE with truncation level of 5% is 8.278.

mean(H_1W.5*(dat$wage[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]-m1.5)+m1.5 - (H_0W.5*(dat$wage[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]-m0.5)+m0.5))
## [1] 8.277714

Bootstrap Result

Additionally, the bootstrap results for AIPW estimators are shown in the following figure. Estimates from AIPW without truncation (left panel) and with truncation level 5% (right panel) follow a normal distribution, while AIPW with truncation level 1% (middle panel) is sightly bimodal. By theory, the AIPW should be asymptotically normal if a consistent estimator predicts $ g$ and \(m\).

Targeted maximum likelihood estimation (TMLE)

The TMLE estimator is:

\[ \hat{\theta}_{TMLE} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \bigg[ \tilde{m}(A_i,W_i) \bigg] \]

where \(\tilde{m}(A,W)\) denotes the targeted estimate of the conditional mean outcome, given the exposure and baseline covariates \(\mathrm{E}(Y|A,W)\). Similar to AIPW, implementation requires estimation of \(\mathrm{E}(Y|A,W)\) and \(g(W)=\mathrm{P}(A=1|W)\). TMLE is also a double robust estimator and if both \(\mathrm{E}(Y|A,W)\) and \(\mathrm{P}(A|W)\) are estimated consistently, TMLE will be efficient. As TMLE will generate values in our target range, it will be preferred. These asymptotic properties describe what happens when sample size goes to infinity and also translates into lower bias and variance in finite samples.

SuperLearner Result

The estimated ATE using hand code TMLE is 3.569.

logit_update<- lm(dat$wage ~ -1 + offset(ma) + H_AW)
epsilon = coef(logit_update)

expY_givenAW_star = ma+epsilon*H_AW
expY_given1W_star = m1+epsilon*H_1W
expY_given0W_star = m0+epsilon*H_0W

estimates <- mean(expY_given1W_star-expY_given0W_star)
estimates
## [1] 3.569167

Similarly, 1% and 5% truncation levels were applied to TMLE estimator.

The estimated ATE using hand-code TMLE is 3.648, with 1% truncation.

ma.1 = ma[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]
logit_update.1<- lm(dat$wage[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)] ~ -1 + offset(ma.1) + H_AW.1)
epsilon.1 = coef(logit_update.1)

expY_given1W_star.1 = m1.1+epsilon.1*H_1W.1
expY_given0W_star.1 = m0.1+epsilon.1*H_0W.1
mean(expY_given1W_star.1-expY_given0W_star.1)
## [1] 3.648097

The estimated ATE using hand code TMLE is 3.662 with 5% truncation.

ma.5 = ma[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]
logit_update.5<- lm(dat$wage[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)] ~ -1 + offset(ma.5) + H_AW.5)
epsilon.5 = coef(logit_update.5)

expY_given1W_star.5 = m1.5+epsilon.5*H_1W.5
expY_given0W_star.5 = m0.5+epsilon.5*H_0W.5
mean(expY_given1W_star.5-expY_given0W_star.5)
## [1] 3.661799

     Q.SL.library = outcome_library,
     g.SL.library = exposure_library)
save(t, file = "est_tmle_function.Rdata")

Bootstrap Result

The bootstrap results for TMLE estimators are shown in the following figure. All three estimators seem to follow a normal distribution, which is consistent with the theory that TMLE is of asymptotical linearity and normality under a condition in which consistent estimators predict both \(g\) and \(m\).

boot.t %>%
  select("TMLE", "TMLE (truncated 1%)","TmLE (truncated 5%)") %>%

In general, the truncation of \(g(W)\) increases the point estimate of IPTW, AIPW, and TMLE estimators, and the estimate increases as the truncation level increases from 1% to 5%. The standard error of estimates also increases slightly with the increase of truncation level, except the TMLE estimator, the standard error are similar.

The substitution estimator has the smallest standard error. This may due to better libraries used for estimating \(m(W)\), and our estimated \(\hat{m}(W)\) is closer to the true \(m(W)\). TMLE estimators also ahve a small standard error, while AIPW estimators have the largest standard error among these estimators.

Most of the 95% CI do not contain 0, indicating that the difference of wage comparing all subjects in the study with information job class to all subjects in the study with industrial job class is significantly different 0, and there is a positive effect of information job class comparing to industrial job class on the wage of males from the Atlantic region of the United States. Only the normal approximation CI of AIPW estimators without truncation and 1% truncation level contain 0 because these two estimators have a larger standard error. Besides, the bootstrap results of AIPW without truncation is a little right-skewed, and the distribution of AIPW estimator with 1% truncation has two peaks. Their 95% quantile CI do not contain 0.

We will choose TMLE estimator without truncation as our final estimator because our \(g(W)\) is away from 0. The estimated difference of wage comparing all subjects in the study with information job class to all subjects in the study with industrial job class is 3.569, with 95% CI (1.359, 5.824). Under a 0.05 level of significance, the difference is significantly different from 0, and the causal effect of job class on wage is significant.

Step 7: Conclusion

Four estimators were applied to estimate the causal effect of job class on the wage of males from the Atlantic region of the United States. We found that information job class will cause a higher wage in such a population, and it is estimated using TMLE that the difference is 3.569 with 95% CI (1.359, 5.824). The difference in wages in these two job classes may indicate that as information job class was a fast-developing job market in 2011, employees in the information field are likely to earn a higher wage than industrial. Also, companies in the information field may have higher profits so that they can afford and are willing to pay a higher wage.

This study also has several limitations. The population of this study is small. Further study may focus on both males and females in all regions of the United States. Also, time series analysis may also be applied to separate the effect of inflation from wages so that we can study the effect of job class itself more accurately. More variables, including family background, may also be included, as well as a larger library of a super learner, to improve our model.

Code book

age - continuous, age that wage information was recorded

race - race

  • race = 1: White
  • race = 2: Black
  • race = 3: Asian
  • race = 4: Other

education - education level

  • education = 1: <HS Grad
  • education = 2: HS Grad
  • education = 3: Some College
  • education = 4: College Grad
  • education = 5: Advanced Degree

maritl - marital status

  • maritl = 1: Never Married
  • maritl = 2: Married
  • maritl = 3: Widowed
  • maritl = 4: Divorced
  • maritl = 5: Separated

health - health level of worker

  • health = 1: <= Good
  • health = 2: >= Very Good

year - continuous, year that wage information was recorded

health_ins - whether worker has health insurance

  • health_ins = 1: Yes
  • health_ins = 2: No

jobclass - type of job

  • jobclass = 1: Industrial
  • jobclass = 2: Information

knn.tune = CV.SuperLearner(Y=dat$A, X=dplyr::select(X, -A),
                          family = binomial(), V=5,
                          SL.library = knn.learners$names,
                          parallel = cluster)
save(knn.tune, file = "knn.exposure.Rdata")

Using 5-fold cross validation, the tuned KNN for exposure has 50 neighbours. It has the lowest risk and small se.

Bootstrap Results

The function used to estimate the causal effect using the four estimators(G-Computation, IPTW, AIPW, TMLE) is shown as follows.

# Define function to estimate causal effect using the four estimators.
four_est = function(data,indices,SL.m,SL.g){
  # resampling
  data = data[indices,]
  W = data[,c(1:5,8:9)]
  A = data$A
  Y = data$wage
  
  ## G-computation
  X = cbind(W,A)
  X1 = cbind(W,1)
  X0 = cbind(W,0)
  colnames(X) = letters[1:ncol(X)]
  colnames(X1) = letters[1:ncol(X1)]
  colnames(X0) = letters[1:ncol(X0)]
  
  SL.outcome = snowSuperLearner(Y = Y, X = X, family = gaussian(),
                                # For a real analysis we would use V = 10.
                                cvControl = list(V=10), 
                                # paralell computing: 6 cores
                                cluster = cluster,
                                SL.library = outcome_library)
  
  ma = predict(SL.outcome, newdata = X, onlySL = TRUE)$pred
  m1 = predict(SL.outcome, newdata = X1, onlySL = TRUE)$pred
  m0 = predict(SL.outcome, newdata = X0, onlySL = TRUE)$pred
  sub_est = mean(m1-m0)
  
  ## IPTW
  SL.exposure = snowSuperLearner(Y=A,X=W,family = binomial(),
                                 cvControl = list(V=10), 
                                 SL.library = exposure_library,
                                 cluster=cluster)
  gw = SL.exposure$SL.predict
  H_AW = (A==1)/gw - (A==0)/(1-gw)
  H_1W = 1/gw
  H_0W = -1/(1-gw)
  iptw.est = mean(H_AW*Y)
  
  # IPTW truncated
  gw.1 = gw[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]
  gw.5 = gw[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]
  H_AW.1 = H_AW[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]
  H_AW.5 = H_AW[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]
  H_1W.1 = 1/gw.1
  H_1W.5 = 1/gw.5
  H_0W.1 = -1/(1-gw.1)
  H_0W.5 = -1/(1-gw.5)
  ## truncated 1%
  iptw.est.truncated.001 = mean(H_AW.1*Y[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)])
  ## truncated 5%
  iptw.est.truncated.005 =  mean(H_AW.5*Y[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)])
  
  ## AIPW 
  aipw.est = mean(H_1W*(Y-m1)+m1 - (H_0W*(Y-m0)+m0))
  # truncate
  m1.1 = m1[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]
  m1.5 = m1[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]
  m0.1 = m0[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]
  m0.5 = m0[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]
  ## truncated 1%
  aipw.est.trunc001=mean(H_1W.1*(Y[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]-m1.1)+m1.1 -
                           (H_0W.1*(Y[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]-m0.1)+m0.1))
  ## truncated 1%
  aipw.est.trunc005=mean(H_1W.5*(Y[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]-m1.5)+m1.5 -
                           (H_0W.5*(Y[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]-m0.5)+m0.5))
  
  ## TMLE
  lm_update = lm(Y~-1+offset(ma)+H_AW)
  epsilon = coef(lm_update)
  expY_givenAW_star = ma+epsilon*H_AW
  expY_given1W_star = m1+epsilon*H_1W
  expY_given0W_star = m0+epsilon*H_0W
  tmle.est = mean(expY_given1W_star-expY_given0W_star)
  # # truncated 1%
  ma.1 = ma[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)]
  lm_update.1<- lm(Y[gw>quantile(gw, 0.01)] ~ -1 + offset(ma.1) + H_AW.1)
  epsilon.1 = coef(lm_update.1)
  expY_given1W_star.1 = m1.1+epsilon.1*H_1W.1
  expY_given0W_star.1 = m0.1+epsilon.1*H_0W.1
  tmle.est.trunc001=mean(expY_given1W_star.1-expY_given0W_star.1)
  # # truncated 5%
  ma.5 = ma[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)]
  lm_update.5<- lm(Y[gw>quantile(gw, 0.05)] ~ -1 + offset(ma.5) + H_AW.5)
  epsilon.5 = coef(lm_update.5)
  expY_given1W_star.5 = m1.5+epsilon.5*H_1W.5
  expY_given0W_star.5 = m0.5+epsilon.5*H_0W.5
  tmle.est.trunc005=mean(expY_given1W_star.5-expY_given0W_star.5)

  return(c(sub_est,iptw.est,iptw.est.truncated.001,iptw.est.truncated.005,
           aipw.est,aipw.est.trunc001,aipw.est.trunc005,
           tmle.est,tmle.est.trunc001,tmle.est.trunc005
           ))
}
clusterExport(cluster, outcome_library)
clusterExport(cluster, exposure_library)
clusterExport(cluster, "four_est")
results = boot(data=dat, statistic = four_est, R = 100,
               SL.m = outcome_library, SL.g = exposure_library,
               parallel = "snow", cl = cluster)
